          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \gamma ={\frac {1}{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/8b130ec5e5e9586833b7888f7cbe2433f1e295e3" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -3.171ex; width:16.929ex; height:6.509ex;" alt="\gamma ={\frac {1}{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}}"/></span><span about="#mwt403">
</span></dd></dl>

<p id="mwAks">The invariant mass of systems is the same for observers in all inertial frames, while the relativistic mass depends on the observer's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Frame_of_reference" title="Frame of reference" id="mwAkw">frame of reference</a>. In order to formulate the equations of physics such that mass values do not change between observers, it is convenient to use rest mass. The rest mass of a body is also related to its energy <i id="mwAk0">E</i> and the magnitude of its momentum <b id="mwAk4">p</b> by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Relativistic_energy-momentum_equation" title="Relativistic energy-momentum equation" id="mwAk8" class="mw-redirect">relativistic energy-momentum equation</a>:</p>

<dl id="mwAlA"><dd id="mwAlE"><span class="mwe-math-element" typeof="mw:Extension/math" about="#mwt405" data-mw='{"name":"math","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":"(m_\\mathrm{rest})c^2=\\sqrt{E_\\mathrm{total}^2-(|\\mathbf{p}|c)^2}.\\!"}}' id="mwAlI"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle (m_{\mathrm {rest} })c^{2}={\sqrt {E_{\mathrm {total} }^{2}-(|\mathbf {p} |c)^{2}}}.\!}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <msub>
